Rule: PGM109
Severity: MINOR
Description: Column uses floating-point type instead of numeric

PGM109 — Floating-point column type

What it detects:
A column declared as `real`, `float4`, `double precision`, `float8`, or
`float` in CREATE TABLE, ADD COLUMN, or ALTER COLUMN TYPE.

Why it's problematic:
IEEE 754 floating-point types suffer from precision issues — for example,
`0.1 + 0.2 ≠ 0.3`. For money, quantities, measurements, or any domain
where exact decimal values matter, `numeric`/`decimal` is correct.
Floating-point errors compound in aggregations and can cause silent data
corruption.

Example (bad):
CREATE TABLE products (price double precision NOT NULL);

Fix:
CREATE TABLE products (price numeric(10,2) NOT NULL);
